// Man page for nmap
manNmap="NMAP(8)                          X Shell Manual                          NMAP(8)

<b>NAME</b>
    nmap - network port mapper
<b>SYNOPSIS</b>
    <b>nmap </b>(<b>--post</b>) (<b>-w</b>) <b>IP|DOMAIN</b>
    <b>nmap </b>(<b>--post</b>) (<b>-w</b>) <b>-l</b>
    <b>nmap </b>(<b>--post</b>) (<b>-w</b>) <b>-p</b>
    <b>nmap </b>(<b>--post</b>) (<b>-w</b>) <b>-r</b>
    <b>nmap -sn PUBLIC_IP</b>
<b>DESCRIPTION</b>
    Scan remote IPs and domains to discover open ports and services. Essential reconnaissance
    tool for network mapping and security assessment. Supports localhost, public IP, random IP
    scanning. Use redirects to save output to files without printing to terminal. Combine with
    --post flag to pass scan results as parameters to other commands.
<b>OPTIONS</b>
    <b>IP|DOMAIN</b>
    Scan specific target
    Find open ports and services

    <b>-l</b>
    Scan localhost
    Check local open ports

    <b>-p</b>
    Scan public IP
    Check own public IP ports

    <b>-r</b>
    Scan random IP
    Random target reconnaissance

    <b>-w</b>
    Show whois + recon data
    Display whois registration, router version, and firewall rules

    <b>-sn</b> <b>PUBLIC_IP</b>
    Discover all devices on the LAN behind the router at PUBLIC_IP.
    Automatically recurses into sub-routers.
      [Edge Router]  the top-level router
      [Router]       a sub-router (recursed into automatically)
      [Device]       an end device
<b>EXAMPLE:</b>
    <color=#e4ff34># Target Scanning</color>
    <b>nmap 192.168.1.1</b>
    Scan specific IP

    <b>nmap example.com</b>
    Scan domain

    <b>nmap server.local</b>
    Scan local server

    <color=#e4ff34># Special Targets</color>
    <b>nmap -l</b>
    Scan localhost

    <b>nmap -p</b>
    Scan public IP

    <b>nmap -r</b>
    Scan random IP

    <color=#e4ff34># Whois Lookup</color>
    <b>nmap -w 155.236.80.20</b>
    Scan ports + show whois data

    <b>nmap -w -r</b>
    Scan random IP with whois

    <color=#e4ff34># Ping Sweep</color>
    <b>nmap -sn 1.2.3.4</b>
    Discover devices on the LAN behind router at 1.2.3.4

    <color=#e4ff34># With Redirects</color>
    <b>nmap 192.168.1.1 > scan.txt</b>
    Save to file

    <b>nmap --post params</b>
    Pass as parameters

    <b>nmap target >> results.txt</b>
    Append to file

    <color=#e4ff34># Pipe Examples</color>
    <b>bc ip | tee scan_target.txt | nmap | grep open</b>
    Scan random IP and save target to file

    <b>cat targets.txt | nmap</b>
    Scan IP from file

    <b>echo 192.168.1.1 | nmap | grep -i http</b>
    Scan and filter for HTTP ports
<b>SEE ALSO</b>
    <b>scan</b>, <b>nslookup</b>, <b>whois</b>, <b>tee</b>"